initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent breakthroughs, natural language processing (NLP) models have demonstrated unparalleled success in sentiment analysis and language translation tasks. Graph attentional neural networks (GANNs) are proposed as a novel extension to traditional NLP models by incorporating graph theoretical frameworks. The incorporation of graphs allows for an efficient propagation of information between entities, reducing the complexity of input data from O(n^2) to O(log n). This paper implements and compares both traditional NLP models and GANNs by testing classification accuracy and interpretability on four commonly used datasets. The datasets include IMDB movie reviews, Twitter sentiment, Yahoo! Answers, and Wikipedia article revisions. Moreover, attention mechanisms, a technique commonly used in NLP to highlight informative text segments, is also integrated into GANNs. Contrary to expectations, the results reveal that attention mechanisms did not exhibit a significant impact on GANNs' performance. The underlying factors and implications behind this discovery are analyzed, aiming to broaden our comprehension of neural graph theories and applications.

Innovative machine learning models have been harnessed to tackle complex pattern recognition tasks in medical imaging. A novel approach, fusion neural networks (FNNs), is proposed to merge the strengths of traditional convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and recurrent neural networks (RNNs). By integrating spatial and temporal relationships, FNNs facilitate the efficient extraction of meaningful features from volumetric data, effectively reducing the complexity of image processing from O(n^3) to O(n^2). This study presents a comprehensive evaluation of FNNs and CNNs on three challenging datasets, featuring cardiac MRI, CT scans, and breast cancer histopathology images. Furthermore, multi-task learning, a technique often employed in medical imaging to leverage redundant information, is incorporated into FNNs. Surprisingly, the results demonstrate that FNNs outperform CNNs on specific classification tasks, highlighting the potential of FNNs to revolutionize medical diagnosis and patient care.
